<lb n="05" break="no"/>ης</w> <w lemma="καί" rend="καὶ">καὶ</w> <w lemma="ὁ" rend="ἡ ">ἡ</w> <w lemma="γυνή" rend="γυνὴ">γυνὴ</w> <space/> <w>Στρατονίκη</w>
<lb n="06"/><w>Σαράπιδι</w> <w>Ἴσιδι</w> <space/> <w lemma="ὁ" rend="τὸ">τὸ</w> <w lemma="τέμενος" rend="τέμενος">τέμενος</w>
</ab>
</div>
            <div type="apparatus"> <!-- references in note will go in @source on app once bibliography is encoded -->
                <p/>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>In favour of Κing Ptolemy, the son of Ptolemy and Berenike, Soteres, Archagathos the son of Agathokles, the governor of Libya, and his wife Stratonike (dedicated) the sanctuary to Sarapis and Isis.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>This ‘strikingly fine’ (Bagnall 1976, 175) dedication of a sanctuary to Sarapis and Isis for Ptolemy II and Berenike I is of particular interest for the persons and office of its dedicators, Archagathos, epistatês of Libya (Pros. Ptol. VI, 14495), and his wife Stratonike. The joint dedication of a sanctuary by a husband and wife is unusual, and the inscription is cut in imposing early third-century lettering on a substantial plaque.</p>
            </div>
